{"Title":"Customizing ObjectCloud","Contents":"\n<p>ObjectCloud is designed for easy customization. Its templating system allows you use ObjectCloud with your own look and feel for the beginnings of a custom-branded social network.</p><p>In order to customize ObjectCloud, you will need a working knowledge of HTML, CSS, and image editing. Basic&#160;familiarity&#160;with XML is helpful. Generally speaking, we try to develop ObjectCloud in a way that someone who's spent a few hours with a \"how to make a web page in HTML and CSS\" will be comfortable following the <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/customize walkthough.page\">walkthrough</a>.</p><h1>Quick Start: Walkthrough</h1><p>Step-by-step instructions on how I <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/customize walkthough.page\">turned a default ObjectCloud installation into Andrew Rondeau's personal web page</a>.&#160;</p><h1>Customization Overview</h1><p>ObjectCloud is designed so that most customizations occur in <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/DefaultTemplate\">/DefaultTemplate</a>. This folder contains images, CSS, and components with partial xhtml documents. ObjectCloud assembles these incomplete components into complete xhtml documents. You are free to alter the images, css, and components to your liking. Future versions of ObjectCloud will add additional files to <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/DefaultTemplate\">/DefaultTemplate</a>.</p><p>Most of ObjectCloud's runtime Javascript is in <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Shell\">/Shell</a>. The contents of /Shell change rapidly between versions, thus it is best to avoid changing these files. <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Shell\">/Shell</a>&#160;works with components in <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/DefaultTemplate\">/DefaultTemplate</a>&#160;through&#160;well-known ids, classes, and form names. Typically, when editing components in <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/DefaultTemplate\">/DefaultTemplate</a>, you shouldn't change class names, ids, and form names.</p><p>ObjectCloud looks for these ids, classes, and form names. For example, <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/DefaultTemplate/login.oc?Method=ReadAll\">/DefaultTemplate/login.oc</a>&#160;uses&#160;<a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Shell/Security/Login.js\">/Shell/Security/Login.js</a>&#160;to log the user in through AJAX. The Javascript looks for buttons of class Login_logoutButton to register the login handler. Changing the login button to another class will break the login dialog box.</p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"/><meta charset=\"utf-8\"/><meta charset=\"utf-8\"/><p>In summary:</p><p></p><ul><li>Everything in /DefaultTemplate is customizable.</li><li>ObjectCloud's Javascript in /Shell uses /DefaultTemplate. Changing Javascript in /Shell is discouraged because we update it regularly with each release.</li><li>Avoid changing classes, ids, and form names as ObjectCloud's Javascript uses these.</li><li>We generally will add to /DefaultTemplate in new versions, but be aware that we might make changes in early versions that will require you to update your customizations.</li></ul><p></p><h1>/DefaultTemplate contents</h1><p>The following files are in /DefaultTemplate:</p><p></p><ul><li></li><li><b>createaccount.oc</b>: Component used to create an account.</li><li><b>default.css</b>: The default css used with every page.</li><li><b>empty.ochf</b>: Base HTML used for pages that have no header, footer, or navbar</li><li><b>group.oc</b>: Component that displays information about a group.</li><li><b>header.png</b>: 1-pixel-wide image used in the header to generate a fade effect.</li><li><b>headerfooter.ochf</b>: Default base HTML for most ObjectCloud pages, includes the headers and footers.</li><li><b>images</b>: Folder for images from <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://jqueryui.com/\">jQueryUI</a>.</li><li><b>jquery-ui.css</b>: <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://jqueryui.com/\">jQueryUI</a>'s CSS.</li><li><b>login.oc</b>: Component that prompts the user to log in.</li><li><b>login.occ</b>: Displays a link to log in if the user isn't logged in, or displays some basic session information when the user is logged in.</li><li><b>navbar.oc</b>: The menu on the left.</li><li><b>noprofile.jpg</b>: Shown when the current user hasn't set up an avatar. (Profile picture)</li><li><b>notification.occ</b>: Template for each notification. This is heavily manipulated in Javascript to merge replies under a single object.</li><li><b>objectbar.ochf</b>: Top bar shown when displaying objects, such as pages.</li><li><b>openidlandingpage.oc</b>: Shown when a local user is logging into another server through OpenID.</li><li><b>particle.css</b>: CSS used when showing notifications.</li><li><b>particle.oc</b>: High-level component for showing notifications.</li><li><b>permissiondenied.oc</b>: Shown when a user doesn't have permission to view the requested page.</li><li><b>profile.oc</b>: User's profile page, currently not implemented.</li><li><b>root.jpg</b>: Default avatar for root.</li><li><b>status.oc</b>: Component for a user to post a status.</li><li><b>upload.oc</b>: Page to guide a user in uploading. Currently unimplemented.</li><li><b>usermanager.oc</b>: Page for allowing a user to manage his or her account.</li></ul><p></p>"}